{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_bellatrix_ver03/data/sn89075140/00415665921/1923091201/0832.xml":{"full_text":"FARMING NEWS REVIEW\nL _\nFARM EQUIPMENT i\nMore than $7,000,000,000.00 must j\nbe invested in new farm equipment\nand improvements within the next\ndecade, economists estimate.\nFor years the farmer has patched,\nmended, and denied himself. The\ntime is coming when it will be neces\nsary tor him to make good deprecia\ntion just as the railroads have done.\nThree-quarters of the farm build\nings will need new roofs and new\npaint, and many thousands of new\nstructures will have to be erected.\nMachinery plays such an important\npart in farm operations that total\nequipment is much more complex\nthan a generation ago.\nReplacements and improvements\nspell a return of prosperity for the>\nimplement concerns. How the farm- j\ner will provide the funds is a ques\ntion.' The wise farmer will set aside j\na percentage of his gross income;\nevery year for depreciation, so that\nhe will not have to borrow when the j\ntime comes to buy a new reaper or\nerect a new cow shed. 1\nCORN BORJ5R\nThe corn-borer patrols, establish\ned in various localities, are by no\nmeans an idle and unnecessary pre\ncaution. The ilittle insect consti-\ntutes\u00bbone of the worst threats to\nthe corn crop which this country\nvhas ever faced.\nNine states of America\u2019s corn belt\nproduce G5 per cent of the country\u2019s\ncorn, while the United States grows\n75 per cent of the world\u2019s corn. It\nis importan that every farmer co-;\noperate with the state and federal\ndepartments in the extermination of\nthis pest.\nThe corn borer can destroy an en\ntire field of corn unless held in\ncheck, and the expense of measures\ntaken against it add greatly to\nthe cost of raising corn. The corn\ncrop covers 118,901,000 acres of the\nnation's richest farm lands and has\na total value of $4,000,000,000.00. It\nmust be protected. s\nREALY PROFITABLE\nFarming unquestionably will be\ncome more profitable with the passr\ning of years: Farmers 25 years\nhence may recall with jocularity the\nfact that in 1923 wheat sold at a\nloss.\nThe fact must always be remem\nbered that farming is a staple in\ndustry, and as such is pretty sure\nof earning fair dividends, although\ndenied the bonanzas of more specu\nlative industries., I)r. L. C. Gray,\neconomist of the department of\n\\griculture, points out that a steadily\nincreasing .'population will reAice\nthe per capita acreage in crops and\npasture. The area still available for\nfanning is mostly of low fertility.'\nForests will compete with crops for,\nthe remaining humid area, and for-'\nestation can no longer be neglected.\nAmerica is at a turning point. It\nhas passed the high point in area of\nfarm lands relative to population.\nConditions will grow more favor\nable to agriculture, and this coun\ntry may some day have to import in\nstead of export .food. I\nMfVRioMT^KRvrroiic viiw_C4V**wjro\u00abitf\nWOMAN IS FIRST ENTRANT IN AIR RACE\nMrs. Bertha Dale Horchem, of Ransom, Kan., who was the first\nof 250 entries for the International Air Races of 1923. to be held at\nSt Louis Field, October 1, 2 and 3. The prize for the/ winner is a\nvaluable trophy in addition to the cash prize of $1,000. Recently Mrs.\nHorchem established a new altitude record for women by ascending\n16,300 feet at the St. Louis Aviation Field, breaking the previous mark\nof 15,700 feet held by Andree Peyre of France. Photo shows Cyle and\nBertha Horchem.\nRETAIL TTADE CONDITIONS\nSeptember Brings Seasonal Turn In\nMercantile Lines\u2014People De\nmanding Sound Values.\nr Labor Day usually brings a spurt\nin retail buying.\nWith tlie opening of school at\nhand, families are returning from\ntheir vacations and making pur\nchases. Retailers, are 'first affected,\nbut the recovery shows itself to\n_ some extent in wholesale markets.\nRetailers and wholesalers are still\ncautious and await the beginning of\nautumn trade in earnest within the\nnext week or ten days. Confidence\nis somewhat greater than heretofore.\nThe importance of wheat in the\nfarmer\u2019s budget has doubtless been\nexaggerated ,and other products en\njoy a more favorable status. The.\nvolume of goods which the country\nis consuming is remarkable in view\nof the existing agricultural depress\nion. Mail order houses report a\nbig business.\nBuying power is well Sustained\nthe country over. August showed a\nmoderate improvement over June\ni and July\u2014this despite the limita\ntion upon foreign markets. The\nquestion is asked, \u201cWill this buying\ncontinue?\u201d Probably not without\nfluctuations., Nevertheless a country\nlike the United States need not be\ndependent' upon foreign outlets.\nThis counry is capable of produc\ning within its own borders almost\nevery commodity it really needs and,\ncan arrange, if given a sufficient\nlength of time, do produce only such\nquanities. as the /domestic market\ncan absorb. Trade is a matter of\nadjustment* and the component Sec\ntions of a country blessed with var\nied natural resources and a diversity\nl of industries may trade m\u00bb**ve*\u2018>\nthemselves almost exculsively, if\nthey desire.\nMercantile establishments are in\ngood condition; generaUy speaking,\nand, the number of business, failures\nhas declined, due to cautious man\nagement. There has been compara\ntively little speculative buying. It\nis remarked that, for this reason,\nstocks on reaiIeVs| shelved. are\nfresher' and nforC appealing than in.\nBQgie years. The progressive mer\nchant is alert to note' the public\nneeds and desires land provide for\nthem. v\ny Hie trend of prices is not such as\nto discourage buying.* As*for goods,\npeople are demanding sound values\nand getting them, points out one\nbank in the central region. Savings\ndeposits are increasing, and Will act\nas a stabilizer and insurance against\u2019,\nextreme depression and distress.\nThe market is a buyer\u2019s' rather, than\ny\u201ea seller\u2019s market >,f/*\u25a0.,.\nAltogether, from the merchant\u2019s\nK Standpoint, the outlook is satisface\nory. A good trade is apparently as\nsured forttae next three months with\nan excellent holiday business to top\nit off. Credit conditions are favor\nable and few retailers are over-ex\npended and facing serious embar\nrassment.\nShe Cc.-iird After- Mamma.\n\"Did your playrqate enjoy her\nvisit?\u201d said a mother to her small\ndaughter, who had just bidden adieu\ni to a little friend.\n\u201cWhy, yes, mother; I think she\ndid,\u201d replied the child. \u201cI called her\nrmy dear\u2019 very often In that dressy\ntone you use when-you have com\nnany.\u201d\nDamaging a Headstone.\nConway, England, Is sorely trou*\nbled over the fact that the grave\nstone in'the churchyard which Is as\nsociated with Wordsworth\u2019s poem,\n\u201dWe Are Seven,\u201d has been seriously\ndamaged by the enthusiastic tripper.\nOpe bit after another has been chip\nped oft, and if the destruction is al\nlowed to continue, nothing of the\nstone will soon be \"left.\nThe Stories or famous Novels\nBy Albert Payson Terhune\nCAMILLE\nBy. Alexander Dumas, Jr.\nMarguerite Gauthier, by birth a\nFrench peasant girl, came to Paris\nwhen she was little more than a child.\nThere her beauty, her wit and a name\nless charm that waf hers brought her\nat once Into notoriety.\nNobles and rich merchants sued for\nher favor. She numbered her adorers\nby the hundred. Her dresses and man\nnerisms were slavishly copied by less\nfascinating women. Her lightest whim\nin costume or coiffure was enough to\nsot a fashion. Even her custom of\nwearing a single white or blood-red\ncamellia in her hair or ball gown was\nnoticed and wondered at; and in time\nit gave her the nickname: La Dame\naux Camelias (\u2018The Lady with the\nCamelias\u201d).\nBut if Marguerite Inspired lotfe In\nevery man\u2019s heart no man had ever\nbeen able to stir one spark of affection\nin hers. Cold, her heart unawaken edf\"\nshe moved through the gayest life In\nthe world\u2019s gayest city.\nLate hours and tireless amusement\nseeking began to work havoc on Mar\nguerite\u2019s health. Her lungs became\naffected. .Her doctor ordered her to\ngo away for a long rest. She laughed\nat the command. Rest was not for her,\nnor was absence from her beloved\nParis. She kneV life was ebbing. But\nshe preferred to throw away wliat was\nleft of it in gaiety rather than eke out\nslowly tiie shreds of existence in some\ndull health,resort.\nIt was at this time she met Armand\nDuval, a young fellow from the prov\ninces; poor but ambitious and unused\nto Paris ways. Armand, like everyone\nelse, fell at once and utterly in love\nwith Marguerite Gauthier.\nHe had no wealth to offer her. He\nhad nothing but his all consuming\nlove. And that love, by its very\nstrength, awoke Marguerite\u2019s dormant\naffections.\nArmand was unlike any man she had\nmet in the cheap, vulgar world that\nwas hers. When she was ill and un\nhappy her other admirers used tp stay\naway. But at such times Armand\nwould spend whole nights, in the cold,\nrainy street, looking up ht her win\ndows. His devotion won her. And\nshe gave him heart for h^rt.\n\u201cI shall not live long,\" she told him,\n\u2018\u2018but I shall, outlive your love.\u201d\nHe denied this vehemently. And for\na space they were very happy. But\nscion their romance was ended. Ar\nmahd's father heard of his son's infat\nuation. He journeyed to Paris and had\nan interview with Marguerite. Tear\nfully the old man implored her to give\nup his son.; shewing her how the affair\n-must ruin Amand\u2019s career and cause\nmisery to his family.\n.Marguerite, to avert future sorrow\nfrom the man she loved, consented to\nset Armand free. She chose the only\nmethod that could possibly have cured\nhim of hi3 infatuation for her. She\nmade him believe she was tired of him\nand of their pleasant, quiet life togeth\ner and that she craved the wealth and\nadmiration which had\u2018been hers in\nother days. Also that she cared for\nsomeone else.\nIn fury at her seeming fickleness Ar\nmand showered curses^arid insults up\non her and then left Paris. Marguerite-;\nheartbroken at losing him, fell ill. Ar\nmand learned at last of the sacrifice\n.she had made for him. But he learned\nit too late. For Marguerite Gauthier\nwas dead. 1\n(NOTE\u2014This story was published\nunder the title \"La Dame Aux Camel\nias.\u201d Slightly1 changed, It forms the\nplot of the play \u201cCamille\u201d and of the\nopera \"La Traviata.\u201d Dumas wrote\nthe play from his own novel.)\nALEXANDRE DUMAS the younger\nwas the son of the more famous\nALEXANDER DUMAS and was born\nin July, 1824.\n1 IU| IP IIIQ IIIHI1II1\nFIRST AM'eMCAN TO SWIM THE ENGLISH CHANNEL\ntymy ol Lowell, Maas., fint American to ewim the\nEnglish C hannel, i\u00bb \u00abem receiving part of hia reward a klaa from MW\nWortdell-rupoe juriving at Dover after accompHehing hie heroic\naquatic fegt,: At the right is Mr. Alexandra, who, promised to prea*nt_\n1 a cup to the fitfKtnantoswim the ChandeL\nENGINES AND MACHINERY\nSR *\u00a3t\u00abrr*r<1PnrSj*^iffSSw/'ulr* Cm!\nU'M.. B\nCM?yy. \u00bb____ __\nfor Motraeton sad nwd twillrtmi tatfoa\u2014tD riM;\n*355Z Uixtn. PortnW^ sad Wrtfcw Air u\nPnfunwtk Tools, OtsyhTsm sod CaBtrttusl Pomps oil sfcM.\nolrusss. MorinsEnglnet, OwtwnHn\u00bbsin1 Hnpnlrtm on\nl Jha<ii)}uc dOoo *qu Ganie Work. All untraran aaoak\nv\"\u2018 tbcm\nthh TnL\u00bbno\nMnh! WGIMB COl\nAfter leaving school and sowing a\ncertain quantity of \u201cwild oats\u201d he\nsettled down to serious work. He\nstarted in Action and succeeded: he\nwent on to drama; he took to writing\nabout art, politics, even religion\u2014and\nsucceeded.\nHis novels are all readable. His es\nsays, letters and speeches generally\nare brilliant and admirable in form\nand daring, paradoxical, suggestive in\na very high degree. Of his sixteen\nplays there~ls not one that is not liter\na; are, while many are masterpieces?\nHe is believed 